ltx_toclist\">\n183\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_abstract\"><a href=\"#abstract1\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\">Abstract</span></a></li>\n184\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_section\"><a href=\"#S1\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\">I </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Introduction</span></span></a></li>\n185\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_section\">\n186\t<a href=\"#S2\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\">II </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Related Work</span></span></a>\n187\t<ol class=\"ltx_toclist ltx_toclist_section\">\n188\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S2.SS1\" title=\"In II Related Work ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">II-A</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Ambivalence and Hesitancy Recognition</span></span></a></li>\n189\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S2.SS2\" title=\"In II Related Work ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">II-B</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Multimodal Fusion with Explicit Conflict</span></span></a></li>\n190\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S2.SS3\" title=\"In II Related Work ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">II-C</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Robustness to Speaker Identity</span></span></a></li>\n191\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S2.SS4\" title=\"In II Related Work ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">II-D</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Annotation Uncertainty in Affective Computing</span></span></a></li>\n192\t</ol>\n193\t</li>\n194\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_section\">\n195\t<a href=\"#S3\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\">III </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Method</span></span></a>\n196\t<ol class=\"ltx_toclist ltx_toclist_section\">\n197\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS1\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-A</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Feature Extraction</span></span></a></li>\n198\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS2\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-B</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Temporal Encoding and Pooling</span></span></a></li>\n199\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS3\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-C</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">ConflictFusion</span></span></a></li>\n200\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS4\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-D</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Classifier and Auxiliary Heads</span></span></a></li>\n201\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS5\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-E</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Training Objective</span></span></a></li>\n202\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S3.SS6\" title=\"In III Method ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">III-F</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Prediction</span></span></a></li>\n203\t</ol>\n204\t</li>\n205\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_section\">\n206\t<a href=\"#S4\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\">IV </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Experiments</span></span></a>\n207\t<ol class=\"ltx_toclist ltx_toclist_section\">\n208\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S4.SS1\" title=\"In IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">IV-A</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Dataset and Metrics</span></span></a></li>\n209\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S4.SS2\" title=\"In IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">IV-B</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Implementation Details</span></span></a></li>\n210\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S4.SS3\" title=\"In IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">IV-C</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Main Results</span></span></a></li>\n211\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S4.SS4\" title=\"In IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">IV-D</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Ablation Study</span></span></a></li>\n212\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_subsection\"><a href=\"#S4.SS5\" title=\"In IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text\">IV-E</span> </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Comparison with Prior Work</span></span></a></li>\n213\t</ol>\n214\t</li>\n215\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_section\"><a href=\"#S5\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\"><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_ref\">V </span><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Conclusion</span></span></a></li>\n216\t<li class=\"ltx_tocentry ltx_tocentry_bibliography\"><a href=\"#bib\" title=\"In CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_title\">References</span></a></li>\n217\t</ol></nav>\n218\t</nav>\n219\t<div class=\"ltx_page_main\">\n220\t<div id=\"infobox\" class=\"infobox\">\n221\t  <a id=\"license-tr\" href=\"https://info.arxiv.org/help/license/index.html#licenses-available\">\n222\t    License: CC BY 4.0\n223\t  </a>\n224\t  <div id=\"watermark-tr\">\n225\tarXiv:2607.13976v1 [cs.CV] 15 Jul 2026</div>\n226\t</div><div class=\"ltx_page_content\">\n227\t<article class=\"ltx_document ltx_authors_1line\">\n228\t<h1 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_document\">CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition</h1>\n229\t<div class=\"ltx_authors\">\n230\t<span class=\"ltx_creator ltx_role_author\">\n231\t<span class=\"ltx_personname\">Tung Hung Bui\n232\t</span></span>\n233\t<span class=\"ltx_author_before\">  </span><span class=\"ltx_creator ltx_role_author\">\n234\t<span class=\"ltx_personname\">Hong Hai Nguyen\n235\t</span></span>\n236\t<span class=\"ltx_author_before\">  </span><span class=\"ltx_creator ltx_role_author\">\n237\t<span class=\"ltx_personname\">Van Thong Huynh\n238\t</span></span>\n239\t</div>\n240\t\n241\t<div id=\"abstract1\" class=\"ltx_abstract\">\n242\t<h6 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_abstract\">Abstract</h6>\n243\t<p class=\"ltx_p\">Detecting ambivalence and hesitancy (AH) in unconstrained video is\n244\tchallenging because the target signal is inherently ambiguous and\n245\texpressed through subtle cross-modal incongruence rather than\n246\tprototypical affect.\n247\tWe present CF-Net, a deep multimodal network submitted to the\n248\t3<sup class=\"ltx_sup\">rd</sup> Edition of the AH Video Recognition Challenge\n249\t(ABAW 11<sup class=\"ltx_sup\">th</sup>, ECCV 2026), targeting the BAH dataset.\n250\tCF-Net encodes visual, audio, and transcript streams with frozen\n251\tSigLIP2, HuBERT, and DistilBERT backbones, normalises backbone features\n252\tper speaker to reduce identity leakage, and fuses them via a\n253\tConflictFusion module that explicitly computes pairwise cross-modal\n254\tincongruence.\n255\tTraining combines certainty-weighted focal loss, manifold mixup, and\n256\tmodality dropout; an auxiliary certainty-regression head leverages\n257\tambiguity annotations to stabilise learning on genuinely borderline\n258\tsamples.\n259\tCF-Net achieves a Macro F1 of <span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\">0.7155</span> on the BAH validation set\n260\tand <span class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\">0.7364</span> (AP = 0.7492) on the private challenge test set.</p>\n261\t</div>\n262\t<section id=\"S1\" class=\"ltx_section\">\n263\t<h2 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_section\">\n264\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section\">I </span><span id=\"S1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Introduction</span>\n265\t</h2>\n266\t\n267\t<div id=\"S1.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n268\t<p id=\"S1.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Ambivalence and hesitancy (AH) — the co-occurrence of competing inclinations\n269\tand the reluctance to commit to a behavioural choice — arise in high-stakes\n270\tcommunication contexts with direct clinical and social relevance: motivational\n271\tinterviews aimed at health behaviour change <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>, negotiation,\n272\tand social-skill coaching <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib1\" title=\"Social signal processing: survey of an emerging domain\" class=\"ltx_ref\">23</a>]</cite>.\n273\tRecognising AH from video is fundamentally different from identifying discrete\n274\temotions such as happiness or disgust.\n275\tDiscrete emotions tend to produce correlated responses across face, voice, and\n276\tspeech <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib2\" title=\"A review of affective computing: from unimodal analysis to multimodal fusion\" class=\"ltx_ref\">13</a>]</cite>; AH, by contrast, frequently materialises as\n277\tcross-modal incongruence: a speaker’s words may frame a thought positively\n278\twhile their prosody signals hesitation, or their facial expression remains\n279\tneutral as their lexical choices convey ambivalence <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>.\n280\tThe discriminative signal lies in the disagreement between modalities,\n281\tnot in any single channel.</p>\n282\t</div>\n283\t<div id=\"S1.p2\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n284\t<p id=\"S1.p2.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">The BAH dataset <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>, developed for the ABAW AH challenge\n285\tseries, operationalises these difficulties under\n286\tcontrolled experimental conditions.\n287\tNaturalistic clinical interview recordings from 300 speakers are partitioned\n288\twith strict speaker disjointness across 778 training, 124 validation, and\n289\t525 test clips.\n290\tEach clip carries a binary AH label alongside a per-clip annotator-agreement\n291\tcertainty score; low certainty indicates genuine perceptual ambiguity, not\n292\tlabelling error.\n293\tThree consequences shape the learning problem: (i) the training set is small\n294\trelative to the feature dimensionality of large pre-trained backbones;\n295\t(ii) label noise is structurally present on ambiguous samples; and\n296\t(iii) any system that encodes speaker-specific visual appearance or voice\n297\ttimbre will degrade on the test split, where all speakers are unseen.</p>\n298\t</div>\n299\t<div id=\"S1.p3\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n300\t<p id=\"S1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Prior work on BAH can be grouped into three threads, each addressing a\n301\tsubset of these challenges.\n302\tMultimodal fusion methods improve over unimodal baselines substantially, but\n303\tsimple concatenation implicitly assumes modality correlation and does not\n304\texploit the cross-modal disagreement that defines AH.\n305\tConflict-aware fusion, introduced by Bekhouche et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib7\" title=\"Conflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a>]</cite>,\n306\taddresses this directly by appending pairwise absolute-difference terms\n307\t<math id=\"S1.p3.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"|\\mathbf{e}_{i}-\\mathbf{e}_{j}|\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><msub><mi>𝐞</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>𝐞</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\mathbf{e}_{i}-\\mathbf{e}_{j}|</annotation></semantics></math> to the concatenated embeddings, explicitly\n308\tencoding cross-modal incongruence; this yields the strongest published\n309\tfrozen-backbone result on BAH (val Macro F1 = 0.746).\n310\tFine-tuned large-model approaches such as Team LEYA <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib10\" title=\"Team leya in 10th abaw competition: multimodal ambivalence/hesitancy recognition approach\" class=\"ltx_ref\">14</a>]</cite>\n311\tachieve the highest published validation F1 (0.854) through end-to-end\n312\toptimisation of VideoMAE, Wav2Vec 2.0, and EmotionDistilRoBERTa, but their\n313\tvalidation-to-test gap (0.854 vs. 0.714) signals overfitting to the small\n314\t124-video validation set.\n315\tDomain adaptation methods reduce subject-identity sensitivity in expression\n316\trecognition <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib26\" title=\"Personalized feature translation for expression recognition: an efficient source-free domain adaptation method\" class=\"ltx_ref\">16</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib27\" title=\"Subject-based domain adaptation for facial expression recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">25</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib28\" title=\"Test-time adaptation via cache personalization for facial expression recognition in videos\" class=\"ltx_ref\">17</a>]</cite>,\n317\tbut they require subject-specific data at adaptation time — unavailable\n318\tunder the speaker-disjoint BAH protocol.\n319\tNone of these threads simultaneously handles explicit cross-modal incongruence\n320\tmodelling, speaker-identity removal without requiring adaptation data, and\n321\tprincipled handling of annotation uncertainty.</p>\n322\t</div>\n323\t<div id=\"S1.p4\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n324\t<p id=\"S1.p4.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">We present CF-Net to address all three challenges within a single\n325\tlightweight architecture.\n326\tCF-Net encodes visual, audio, and transcript streams with frozen pre-trained\n327\tbackbones (SigLIP2, HuBERT, DistilBERT), applies per-speaker normalisation\n328\tto the visual and audio outputs to remove the constant speaker-identity\n329\toffset, and fuses the normalised embeddings through a ConflictFusion module\n330\tthat explicitly encodes cross-modal incongruence via pairwise\n331\tabsolute-difference features.\n332\tTraining is guided by certainty-weighted focal loss and an auxiliary\n333\tcertainty-regression head that jointly leverage per-video\n334\tannotator-agreement scores; manifold mixup and modality dropout further\n335\tregularise against the small training set.</p>\n336\t</div>\n337\t<div id=\"S1.p5\" class=\"ltx_para ltx_noindent\">\n338\t<p id=\"S1.p5.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">In summary, our contributions are as follows:</p>\n339\t<ul id=\"S1.I1\" class=\"ltx_itemize\">\n340\t<li id=\"S1.I1.i1\" class=\"ltx_item\" style=\"list-style-type:none;\">\n341\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item\">•</span> \n342\t<div id=\"S1.I1.i1.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n343\t<p id=\"S1.I1.i1.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Introduce CF-Net with a ConflictFusion module that explicitly\n344\trepresents cross-modal incongruence via pairwise absolute-difference\n345\tfeatures over visual, audio, and text embeddings, trained with\n346\tcertainty-weighted focal loss, manifold mixup, and modality dropout.</p>\n347\t</div>\n348\t</li>\n349\t<li id=\"S1.I1.i2\" class=\"ltx_item\" style=\"list-style-type:none;\">\n350\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item\">•</span> \n351\t<div id=\"S1.I1.i2.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n352\t<p id=\"S1.I1.i2.p1.2\" class=\"ltx_p\">Propose per-speaker feature normalisation applied to visual and\n353\taudio backbone outputs before temporal encoding, removing the constant\n354\tspeaker-identity offset while preserving within-speaker variation;\n355\tablation shows a <math id=\"S1.I1.i2.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"+\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mo>+</mo><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math>0.013 gain in validation Macro F1\n356\t(<a href=\"#S4.T2\" title=\"In IV-D Ablation Study ‣ IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">Table</span> <span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">II</span></a>), and the positive val-to-test transfer (<math id=\"S1.I1.i2.p1.2.m2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"+\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mo>+</mo><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math>0.021)\n357\tis consistent with reduced identity overfitting.</p>\n358\t</div>\n359\t</li>\n360\t<li id=\"S1.I1.i3\" class=\"ltx_item\" style=\"list-style-type:none;\">\n361\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item\">•</span> \n362\t<div id=\"S1.I1.i3.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n363\t<p id=\"S1.I1.i3.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Incorporate an auxiliary certainty-regression head and\n364\tcertainty-weighted focal loss that jointly leverage per-video\n365\tannotator-agreement scores to reduce overconfidence on ambiguous samples,\n366\tcontributing cumulatively <math id=\"S1.I1.i3.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"+\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mo>+</mo><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math>0.013 in validation F1 (<a href=\"#S4.T2\" title=\"In IV-D Ablation Study ‣ IV Experiments ‣ CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">Table</span> <span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">II</span></a>).</p>\n367\t</div>\n368\t</li>\n369\t<li id=\"S1.I1.i4\" class=\"ltx_item\" style=\"list-style-type:none;\">\n370\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item\">•</span> \n371\t<div id=\"S1.I1.i4.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n372\t<p id=\"S1.I1.i4.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">CF-Net achieves Macro F1 of <span id=\"S1.I1.i4.p1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\">0.7155</span> on the BAH validation\n373\tset and <span id=\"S1.I1.i4.p1.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\">0.7364</span> (AP = 0.7392) on the 11th ABAW private test,\n374\tcompetitive with the best results from the 10th ABAW challenge\n375\t(BROTHER: 0.747 <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib9\" title=\"Brother: behavioral recognition optimized through heterogeneous ensemble regularization for ambivalence and hesitancy\" class=\"ltx_ref\">12</a>]</cite>;\n376\tConflictAwareAH: 0.715 <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib7\" title=\"Conflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a>]</cite>), with all backbone\n377\tweights frozen and training under 15 minutes on a single GPU.</p>\n378\t</div>\n379\t</li>\n380\t</ul>\n381\t</div>\n382\t</section>\n383\t<section id=\"S2\" class=\"ltx_section\">\n384\t<h2 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_section\">\n385\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section\">II </span><span id=\"S2.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Related Work</span>\n386\t</h2>\n387\t\n388\t<section id=\"S2.SS1\" class=\"ltx_subsection\">\n389\t<h3 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection\">\n390\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection\"><span id=\"S2.SS1.4.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\">II-A</span> </span><span id=\"S2.SS1.5.2\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Ambivalence and Hesitancy Recognition</span>\n391\t</h3>\n392\t\n393\t<div id=\"S2.SS1.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n394\t<p id=\"S2.SS1.p1.2\" class=\"ltx_p\">The ABAW AH challenge series <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>\n395\tprovides the formal benchmarks on which we evaluate.\n396\tGonzález-González et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite> introduced the BAH dataset\n397\tand established a TF-IDF + LinearSVC baseline (val Macro F1 = 0.656),\n398\tdemonstrating that explicit verbal hesitancy markers capture meaningful AH\n399\tsignal even without visual or acoustic information.\n400\tSubsequent challenge editions revealed two recurring patterns: multimodal\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c00bb8b-4b34-42ce-b7e5-4f6192efa17d","uuid":"6e5e787b-2861-4dda-bb21-86fc7e6e14c8","timestamp":"2026-07-16T09:37:54.792Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/cf_net.html","content":"<!DOCTYPE html><html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta http-equiv=\"content-type\" content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\">\n<title>CF-Net: Conflict Fusion with Speaker Normalisation and Certainty Weighting for Ambivalence/Hesitancy Recognition</title>\n<!--Generated on Wed Jul 15 15:56:02 2026 by LaTeXML (version 0.8.8) http://dlmf.nist.gov/LaTeXML/.-->\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1, shrink-to-fit=no\">\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/css/arxiv-html-papers-20260131.css\" type=\"text/css\">\n<script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/arxiv-html-papers-20260131.js\"></script>\n<script>\n  // Restore the saved color scheme preference, or\n  // enact the browser pre