{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-a3fe0033b5e33f73","type":"tool_result","content":"400\tSubsequent challenge editions revealed two recurring patterns: multimodal\n401\tfusion consistently outperforms unimodal baselines, with text features\n402\tcontributing disproportionately; and the validation-to-test generalisation\n403\tgap is large for any system that absorbs speaker-specific identity cues from\n404\tvisual or acoustic backbones, because the BAH splits enforce strict speaker\n405\tdisjointness.\n406\tIn the 10th ABAW challenge (CVPR 2026) <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib12\" title=\"From affect to complex behavior: advancing multimodal human-centered ai at the 10th abaw workshop &amp; competition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">8</a>]</cite>,\n407\tBekhouche et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib7\" title=\"Conflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a>]</cite> employed conflict-aware\n408\tmultimodal fusion (val F1 = 0.746); BROTHER <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib9\" title=\"Brother: behavioral recognition optimized through heterogeneous ensemble regularization for ambivalence and hesitancy\" class=\"ltx_ref\">12</a>]</cite>\n409\tused a heterogeneous ensemble (val F1 <math id=\"S2.SS1.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\approx\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mo>≈</mo><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\approx</annotation></semantics></math> 0.758); Team\n410\tLEYA <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib10\" title=\"Team leya in 10th abaw competition: multimodal ambivalence/hesitancy recognition approach\" class=\"ltx_ref\">14</a>]</cite> achieved the highest published validation\n411\tscore (0.854) through end-to-end fine-tuning of four large backbone models,\n412\tbut their validation-to-test drop (to 0.714 on the labeled test split)\n413\tillustrates the overfitting risk on the small validation set.\n414\tCF-Net targets a different operating point: frozen backbones, lightweight\n415\ttemporal encoders, and certainty-aware training.\n416\tIt achieves val F1 = 0.716 with a positive val-to-test transfer\n417\t(<math id=\"S2.SS1.p1.2.m2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"+\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mo>+</mo><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math>0.021), which is the opposite of the overfitting trend observed in\n418\tthe fine-tuned systems.</p>\n419\t</div>\n420\t</section>\n421\t<section id=\"S2.SS2\" class=\"ltx_subsection\">\n422\t<h3 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection\">\n423\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection\"><span id=\"S2.SS2.4.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\">II-B</span> </span><span id=\"S2.SS2.5.2\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Multimodal Fusion with Explicit Conflict</span>\n424\t</h3>\n425\t\n426\t<div id=\"S2.SS2.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n427\t<p id=\"S2.SS2.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Standard early-fusion and late-fusion strategies average or concatenate\n428\tunimodal representations, implicitly assuming that modality signals are\n429\tcorrelated <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib22\" title=\"Multimodal machine learning: a survey and taxonomy\" class=\"ltx_ref\">1</a>]</cite>.\n430\tThis assumption holds for prototypical emotions but breaks down for AH, where\n431\tthe discriminative signal is precisely the disagreement between channels.\n432\tTensor Fusion Networks (TFN) <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib3\" title=\"Tensor fusion network for multimodal sentiment analysis\" class=\"ltx_ref\">24</a>]</cite> model cross-modal interaction\n433\tthrough outer products, capturing higher-order correlations but at quadratic\n434\tparameter cost; Low-Rank Multimodal Fusion (LMF) <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib23\" title=\"Efficient low-rank multimodal fusion with modality-specific factors\" class=\"ltx_ref\">10</a>]</cite> reduces this\n435\tcost through rank decomposition.\n436\tAttention-based cross-modal pooling <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib24\" title=\"Multimodal transformer for unaligned multimodal language sequences\" class=\"ltx_ref\">20</a>]</cite> learns which\n437\tmodalities are most informative per sample, but the additional parameters risk\n438\toverfitting on small datasets such as BAH.\n439\tConflictFusion <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib7\" title=\"Conflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a>]</cite> takes a structurally different\n440\troute: it appends pairwise absolute-difference terms\n441\t<math id=\"S2.SS2.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"|\\mathbf{e}_{i}-\\mathbf{e}_{j}|\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><msub><mi>𝐞</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>𝐞</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\mathbf{e}_{i}-\\mathbf{e}_{j}|</annotation></semantics></math> to the concatenated modality embeddings,\n442\tproducing a fused vector that grows with cross-modal disagreement.\n443\tThis design adds no trainable parameters to the fusion step itself, making it\n444\twell-suited to the small-data BAH regime.\n445\tWe adopt ConflictFusion as the core fusion mechanism and extend it by feeding\n446\tspeaker-normalised features, ensuring that pairwise differences reflect genuine\n447\taffective incongruence rather than stable between-speaker stylistic differences.</p>\n448\t</div>\n449\t</section>\n450\t<section id=\"S2.SS3\" class=\"ltx_subsection\">\n451\t<h3 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection\">\n452\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection\"><span id=\"S2.SS3.4.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\">II-C</span> </span><span id=\"S2.SS3.5.2\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Robustness to Speaker Identity</span>\n453\t</h3>\n454\t\n455\t<div id=\"S2.SS3.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n456\t<p id=\"S2.SS3.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Speaker-identity leakage — the encoding of a speaker’s appearance and voice\n457\ttimbre by visual and acoustic backbones — is the primary source of\n458\tvalidation-to-test degradation in AH recognition, because the BAH test\n459\tspeakers are entirely unseen <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>.\n460\tIn facial expression recognition, domain adaptation methods have addressed\n461\tanalogous subject-identity shifts: Zeeshan et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib27\" title=\"Subject-based domain adaptation for facial expression recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">25</a>]</cite>\n462\tintroduced subject-based domain adaptation to align feature distributions\n463\tacross subjects; Sharafi et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib26\" title=\"Personalized feature translation for expression recognition: an efficient source-free domain adaptation method\" class=\"ltx_ref\">16</a>]</cite> proposed\n464\tsource-free adaptation that personalises a model using the target subject’s\n465\tunlabelled data; Sharafi et al. <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib28\" title=\"Test-time adaptation via cache personalization for facial expression recognition in videos\" class=\"ltx_ref\">17</a>]</cite> further extended this\n466\tto test-time adaptation via personalised feature caching.\n467\tThese methods are effective in their respective settings but share a common\n468\trequirement — subject-specific data at adaptation or test time — that is\n469\tstructurally incompatible with the BAH protocol.\n470\tText-based models offer a different form of identity immunity: transcripts\n471\tcarry no speaker-level acoustic or visual signal and therefore generalise\n472\tnaturally to unseen speakers <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib7\" title=\"Conflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a>]</cite>.\n473\tModality dropout <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib25\" title=\"Moddrop: adaptive multi-modal gesture recognition\" class=\"ltx_ref\">11</a>]</cite> reduces over-reliance on any\n474\tsingle channel during training.\n475\tWe combine modality dropout with per-speaker normalisation: subtracting the\n476\tspeaker mean from every visual and audio backbone feature removes the identity\n477\toffset at source, with no adaptation procedure and no subject-specific data\n478\trequirement.</p>\n479\t</div>\n480\t</section>\n481\t<section id=\"S2.SS4\" class=\"ltx_subsection\">\n482\t<h3 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection\">\n483\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection\"><span id=\"S2.SS4.4.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\">II-D</span> </span><span id=\"S2.SS4.5.2\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_italic\">Annotation Uncertainty in Affective Computing</span>\n484\t</h3>\n485\t\n486\t<div id=\"S2.SS4.p1\" class=\"ltx_para\">\n487\t<p id=\"S2.SS4.p1.1\" class=\"ltx_p\">Affective states such as AH are inherently subjective, and multi-annotator\n488\tlabelling produces disagreements that carry semantic information: a clip on\n489\twhich annotators agree strongly is perceptually unambiguous, while a contested\n490\tclip is genuinely borderline.\n491\tTreating all training labels as equally reliable is suboptimal under this\n492\tcondition.\n493\tThe BAH dataset quantifies annotation quality through a per-clip certainty\n494\tscore derived from annotator agreement <cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\">[<a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"BAH dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for digital behavioural change\" class=\"ltx_ref\">5</a>]</cite>; low-certainty\n495\tclips indicate genuine perceptual difficulty rather than annotation error.\n496\tInstance weighting by annotator confidence is a natural response: placing\n497\thigher gradient weight on high-certainty samples directs the model toward\n498\treliable signal and reduces the cost of errors on ambiguous ones.\n499\tClosely related are soft-label and label-distribution approaches in emotion\n500\trecognition, which train models on probabilistic rather than one-hot targets\n501\tto reflect inter-annotator spread.\n502\tIn CF-Net, we operationalise BAH certainty in two complementary ways: a\n503\tper-sample focal loss weight <math id=\"S2.SS4.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"w(c)\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">​</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">w(c)</annotation></semantics></math> that scales gradient contribution by\n504\tannotator agreement, and an auxiliary regression head that is supervised to\n505\tpredict the certainty score, regularising the shared fused representation on\n506\tambiguous clips and preventing the model from committing confidently to\n507\tlow-certainty labels.</p>\n508\t</div>\n509\t</section>\n510\t</section>\n511\t<section id=\"S3\" class=\"ltx_section\">\n512\t<h2 class=\"ltx_title ltx_title_section\">\n513\t<span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section\">III </span><span id=\"S3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_smallcaps\">Method</span>\n514\t</h2>\n515\t\n516\t<figure id=\"S3.F1\" class=\"ltx_figure\">\n517\t<div id=\"S3.F1.1\" class=\"ltx_inline-block ltx_align_center ltx_transformed_outer\" style=\"width:345.0pt;height:111.3pt;vertical-align:-0.0pt;\"><span class=\"ltx_transformed_inner\" style=\"transform:translate(-15.8pt,5.1pt) scale(0.916290470213079,0.916290470213079) ;\"><span class=\"ltx_inline-block\"><svg id=\"S3.F1.1.